@NYSLabor I’ve exhausted my UI benefits from unemployment in 2019 but I qualify for Emergency Pandemic assistance. I’m filing weekly benefits, per normal as there doesnt seem to be a separate application for pandemic assistance. I call every single day and have not heard from anyone.

After recovering from Covid-19 and being laid off, I remain grateful for my friends, family, health and my publication @UnearthWomen where I continue to champion women and tell their stories. Thank you @brianstelter for having me on @ReliableSources today! https://t.co/e68wWnBDiW

We don’t know whether we’re still contagious, and the doctor explained it’s too soon to tell if people can re-contract COVID-19 or not. So, we are continuing to wear gloves, masks, and take precautions to both protect ourselves and especially others.
A little over a month ago, I was excited to build out new travel content for a publication I love, a month later I test positive for COVID-19, lose my job, and am forced to navigate this new normal.
A little over a month ago, I was excited to build out new travel content for a publication I love, a month later I test positive for COVID-19, lose my job, and am forced to navigate this new normal.

I still have a cough and Jeff is seemingly back to normal. This could have been A LOT worse (especially given Jeff’s asthma), and for many right now it is. I’m glad we stayed home, isolated ourselves, and chose to heed the warnings of the CDC.

Jeff and I have tested positive for #COVID19. We both started displaying symptoms within a day of each other, which included: a sore throat, high fever, persistent dry cough, bad headaches, runny nose, eye pain, body aches/joint pain, and chills. https://t.co/gLmsilUinB
